added_lines: #!/usr/bin/env python # # Licensed under the Apache License, Version 2.0 (the "License"); you may # not use this file except in compliance with the License. You may obtain # a copy of the License at # # http://www.apache.org/licenses/LICENSE-2.0 # # Unless required by applicable law or agreed to in writing, software # distributed under the License is distributed on an "AS IS" BASIS, WITHOUT # WARRANTIES OR CONDITIONS OF ANY KIND, either express or implied. See the # License for the specific language governing permissions and limitations # under the License. """Javelin makes resources that should survive an upgrade.""" import argparse import subprocess import yaml ADMIN = {} def load_resources(fname='resources.yaml'): """Load the expected resources from a yaml flie.""" return yaml.load(open(fname, 'r')) # def check_images(images): # for image in images: # def create_images(images): # pass # def keystone_token(user='demo', passwd='bogus') def create_resources(conf): # first create keystone level resources, and we need to be admin # for those. admin_token = keystone_token(user='admin', passwd='') create_tenants(admin_token, conf['tenants']) create_users(admin_token, conf['users']) # next create resources in a well known order create_objects(conf['objects']) create_images(conf['images']) create_volumes(conf['volumes']) create_servers(conf['servers']) def get_options(): parser = argparse.ArgumentParser( description='Create and validate a fixed set of OpenStack resources') parser.add_argument( '-C', '--check', help='Check the existence of resources instead of creating') parser.add_argument( '-c', '--creds', help='Where the credentials are stored in bash land') opts = parser.parse_args() return opts def collect_admin_creds(credsfile): required = ('OS_AUTH_URL', 'OS_USERNAME', 'OS_TENANT_NAME', 'OS_PASSWORD') out = subprocess.check_output( 'bash -c "source %s admin admin && set | grep ^OS_"' % credsfile, shell=True) creds = {} for line in out.split('\n'): if '=' in line: k, v = line.split('=') creds[k] = v for r in required: if r not in creds: print("Missing %s in credsfile: %s" % (r, credsfile)) sys.exit(1) return creds def main(): opts = get_options() ADMIN = collect_admin_creds(opts.creds) if __name__ == "__main__": main()

commit_message:
Adding the reserved host disk

This change adds the reserved_host_disk parameter in the nova tuning
section for the undercloud. In that section we already have the
parameters to set the ram_allocation_ration and the
reserved_host_memory.
The value is set to 0 which is the default value for that parameter.
The next step will be to add this param in the nova.tuning guard section
in the image elements.

Change-Id: I933d2c3f194bcc6132c037f2e406340bbd3066f2

commit_message:
Replace XML with JSON for N1kv REST calls

Currently the cisco n1kv plugin handles XML responses from VSM.
This change will replace the httplib2 with requests library and handle
JSON responses from the VSM.

Implements: blueprint cisco-n1kv-json-support

Change-Id: Icd32a6a2ab815ccd24ad86371e927c132e204413

Add graduate-oslo-text spec to juno

Change-Id: I9f4d2e77bb7ccb80eaebf57b79c92043b73b1b17
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/oslo-specs refs/changes/65/98965/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: ===================== Graduating oslo.text ===================== Include the URL of your launchpad blueprint: https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/graduate-oslo-text oslo.text includes modules related to text handling, transformation and encoding. The initial version brings in the existing strutils module which contains utilities compatible with Py3K and older versions of the language. Library Name ============ This library includes some code that may eventually be useful outside of OpenStack, but it does assert some policies and behaviors that are specific to OpenStack, so it was placed in the ``oslo`` namespace package as ``oslo.text``. Contents ======== The code for this library was exported from the incubator before we started using specs documents. See http://git.openstack.org/cgit/openstack/oslo.text * openstack/common/strutils.py * tests/unit/test_strutils.py Early Adopters ============== * Glance * Marconi Implementation ============== Assignee(s) ----------- Primary assignee: Flavio Percoco (flaper87) Other contributors: None Primary Maintainer ------------------ Each graduated library needs a primary maintainer. That may be the same person who started the code, the person who graduated it, or it may be someone who is taking over maintenance duties. If more than one person *who is not already on the oslo-core team* intends to participate as a core reviewer for the new library, list them under "Other Contributors". Primary Maintainer: Flavio Percoco (flaper87) Other Contributors: None Security Contact ---------------- Each graduated library needs a contact for the OpenStack Vulnerability Management team. It may be the same as the primary maintainer, an existing Oslo team member who helps with security issues, or it may be someone else on the development team for the new library. Talk with the Oslo and Vulnerability management teams about who the person is, and make sure they agree to their participation before proceeding. Security Contact: Flavio Percoco (flaper87) Milestones ---------- Target Milestone for completion: Juno-2 Work Items ---------- 1. https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo/CreatingANewLibrary 2. Before the library was exported the API was changed so that USE_LAZY is only evaluated once at startup. That won't work for libraries that are using their own translations, though, since they may be initialized through imports that happen before the application has an opportunity to establish whether it wants lazy translation enabled. We need to correct that, probably by updating _make_translation_func() to work with USE_LAZY at runtime again. 3. Since each consuming app and library will have their own copy of the marker functions, we can remove the global marker functions from gettextutils. Adoption Notes ============== Dependencies ============ * https://blueprints.launchpad.net/oslo/+spec/graduate-oslo-i18n References ========== * Discussion at the Icehouse summit: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/icehouse-oslo-status * Discussion at the Juno summit: https://etherpad.openstack.org/p/juno-oslo-release-plan * https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo/Dependencies * https://wiki.openstack.org/wiki/Oslo/GraduationStatus .. note:: This work is licensed under a Creative Commons Attribution 3.0 Unported License. http://creativecommons.org/licenses/by/3.0/legalcode

commit_message:
Correct scenario specific results table headers

This patch allows to correct VM scenario command results displayed
when calling 'rally task detailed <uuid>' : command's result json
keys are now displayed.

Also add functional test to run in gates to check correct output.

Closes-Bug: #1328451

Change-Id: I7cf2a433e47779beba60c52d23825189e60f51a6

commit_message:
Don't set nova api/conductor workers since nova handles this

The changes to devstack to set nova api/conductor workers to 4 predated
commit 75c96a48fc7e5dfb59d8258142b01422f81b0253 to default the workers
equal to the number of CPUs, so this change just removes the hard-coding
from devstack and relies on nova's defaults for number of workers.

Change-Id: I384fc9eeb7a7eddf4679a6852203307a92d88a93

commit_message:
Raise exception after falling out the loop

Currently, register*node() does not cope well if the service fails
to come up, failing silently in the nova-bm case if the node only
has one MAC, and tossing a UnboundLocalError in the ironic case. Set
a guard value and raise an exception to protect against that.

commit_message:
Ensure routing key is specified in the address for a direct producer

Porting this fix from oslo.messaging.  This fixes the impl_qpid.py
driver to allow it to work with the latest stable upstream QPID broker
(version 0.28).  See the Apache Qpid Jira bug
https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/QPID-5557

commit_message:
Hide secrets from puppet logs

Currently secrets like rabbit_password or os_password are displayed in
puppet logs when changed. This commit changes ceilometer_config type
adding a new parameter that triggers obfuscation of the values in
puppet logs.

Change-Id: I9eb6504220c5337c154bf5ad86c7d22bea64df51
Closes-Bug: #1328448

commit_message:
Remove admin_token from default keystone authentication

This commit changes default keystone authentication to use `admin_tenant_name`,
`admin_user` and `admin_password` instead of `admin_token`.
Using `admin_token` is not going to be useful on other systems.
Trove should use the same kind of config as for the rest of OpenStack, and
shouldn't include `admin_token` in the default pipeline.

Change-Id: Ib7a0cecc28c00f931700122ff908cb7e0d5539e7
Closes-Bug: #1234349

commit_message:
Default to setting secure mode on the integration bridge

Set the fail-mode on the integration bridge to be secure. This means if the agent
is stopped or crashes, and OVS is also restarted, OVS will not program a default
NORMAL action. As soon as the agent is restarted, it will correctly program the
integration bridge.

Change-Id: Icf7e3e14ee747c8ce92c14c95a0a1bbf35986252
Closes-Bug: #1324703
(cherry picked from commit 0412c8a3c43e77c1bb04b0c3ba4b2781fc52e7f8)

commit_message:
Add extension checks for AZ extension tests

On Nova v2/v3 API, a client can get AZ info only when AZ extension is
enabled in Nova API server. A client can know API extension loading
condition through "list API extension" API of Nova.
In Tempest config, users can specify API extensions with alias names.
And AZ extension alias names of v2/v3 are the same "os-availability-zone".

This patch adds the extension checks to AZ API tests.

Change-Id: I77bcde6ada20bf9d5b8856a7849b70f9f76ec7b5

commit_message:
Improve usage of MagicMocks in ML2 and L3 tests

Removes usage of a MagicMock in a case where it's not needed.
Replaces a manual function replacement with a mock.patch call
so it's correctly cleaned up by mock.patch.stopall.

commit_message:
Avoid dead loop when update combination alarm

Dead loop scenario:
1. assume we have threhold alarm C, D
2. then we create combination alarm A with alarm_ids = C, D
3. and we create combination alarm B with alarm_ids = A
4. then we update alarm A with alarm_ids = B
5. then when evaluator alarm state, the two combination alarm is a dead loop

We should avoid such secnarios

The basic idea is that:
* all threshold alarms are good alarm, which definitely have no dependency,
  so there is no dead loop
* all alarms only depend on good alarms are good alarms

Note that we can update an alarm with enabled=False, in such case, no matter
there is a dead loop or not, we will allow it, since it will not be evaluated
in alarm-evaluator service. But the side effect is when we enable an alarm,
we should check dead loop no matter we change the alarm_ids or not.

NOTE: If old environment already has dead loop combination alarms, after
upgrade with this patch, put /alarms/{id} api may not work util dead loop is
removed.

Change-Id: Ic4065db9243fb209026e6f5b154e19a705992607
Closes-Bug: #1309182
(cherry picked from commit 065bff48a5e2c9af33b42fc0c672be18f8e05507)
Conflicts:
	ceilometer/api/controllers/v2.py
git_command: git fetch https://review.opendev.org/openstack/ceilometer refs/changes/69/92069/1 && git format-patch -1 --stdout FETCH_HEAD
added_lines: # if we modify alarm_ids of combination alarm, we should check the # dependency to avoid dead loop when evaluate alarm # change alarm to disabled will ignore the dead loop check if data.type == 'combination' and data.enabled: old_ids = old_alarm['rule']['alarm_ids'] updated_ids = updated_alarm['rule']['alarm_ids'] # if alarm previously is disabled, then we should check dead loop # if alarm_ids has been changed, then we should check dead loop if not old_alarm['enabled'] or set(old_ids) != set(updated_ids): self._assert_combination_alarm_no_dead_loop(data) def _assert_combination_alarm_no_dead_loop(self, new_alarm): # since admin can specify alarm a1 in project p1 to # alarm a2 in project p2, we should check all alarms alarms = list(self.conn.get_alarms(enabled=True)) alarms = [Alarm.from_db_model(alarm) for alarm in alarms] # new_alarm may change the type and alarm_ids, so we must update it for idx in range(len(alarms)): if alarms[idx].alarm_id == new_alarm.alarm_id: alarms[idx] = new_alarm break combination_alarms = set([alarm for alarm in alarms if alarm.type == 'combination']) # good alarms has no dead loop in their dependency good_alarms = set(alarms) - combination_alarms good_alarms = set([alarm.alarm_id for alarm in good_alarms]) while combination_alarms: new_good_alarms = [] for alarm in combination_alarms: for alarm_id in alarm.combination_rule.alarm_ids: if alarm_id not in good_alarms: break else: new_good_alarms.append(alarm) # dead loop detected if not new_good_alarms: break combination_alarms -= set(new_good_alarms) good_alarms.update([alarm.alarm_id for alarm in new_good_alarms]) else: return error = (_('Dead loop detected in alarms %s dependency') % [alarm.alarm_id for alarm in combination_alarms]) pecan.response.translatable_error = error raise wsme.exc.ClientSideError(unicode(error))
